<p>This has been another week working on visualizations. I have
summarized some of the results in a
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160528080207/http://api.plos.org/2012/07/20/example-visualizations-using-the-plos-search-and-alm-apis/">blog
post</ext-link> over at the PLoS API website. One of my current
favorites is the dot chart. PLoS Computational Biology publishes a
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160528080207/http://www.ploscollections.org/article/browseIssue.action?issue=info:doi/10.1371/issue.pcol.v03.i01">collection
of Ten Simple Rules</ext-link>. The dot chart below summarizes the HTML
pageviews, PDF downloads and Mendeley readers for this collection (click
on the image for a larger size).</p>
<fig>
  <graphic mimetype="image" mime-subtype="png" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160528080207im_/http://blogs.plos.org/mfenner/files/2012/07/dotchart2-500x386.png" xlink:title="dotchart2" />
</fig>
<p>On Wednesday I gave a presentation about Article-Level Metrics, using
many of the same visualizations. You can find the slides over at
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160528080207/https://speakerdeck.com/u/mfenner/p/article-level-metrics">Speaker
Deck</ext-link> (my new favorite to upload presentation slides).</p>
